Data The data is details of spotify songs and features of those songs. There are 32,828 observations in the data and 23 variables.

#Reading the data, removing na values
spotify <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2020/2020-01-21/spotify_songs.csv')

spotify <- as.data.table(spotify)

Data Exploration I did some exploratory data analysis to see how I wanted to visualize the data. I removed the duplicate tracks and was left with 30584 observations. There are 6 genre playlists, 24 subgenres in them.

spotify%>%
  summarise_all(n_distinct)
##   track_id track_name track_artist track_popularity track_album_id
## 1    28356      23450        10693              101          22545
##   track_album_name track_album_release_date playlist_name playlist_id
## 1            19744                     4530           449         471
##   playlist_genre playlist_subgenre danceability energy key loudness mode

##   speechiness acousticness instrumentalness liveness valence tempo
## 1        1270         3731             4729     1624    1362 17684
##   duration_ms
## 1       19785
spotify <- spotify %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(str_detect(track_name, "mix", negate = TRUE),
         str_detect(track_album_name, "mix|load|amotion", negate = TRUE))

ANALYSIS

How is the difference in popularity of a song related to its danceability?

Are they positively related? To find out, I drew a plot of danceability and track popularity for each playlist genre. We see that for each individual genre, as the danceability of the track increases, so does its popularity by the upward slope of all genres.

pop_dance <- ggplot(data = spotify, aes(danceability, track_popularity, color = playlist_genre)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, size = 0.8) +
  labs(x = "Danceability of the Track", 
         y = "Popularity on Spotify") +
    theme(axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
          axis.ticks.length.y = unit(5, "pt"),
          axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
          axis.line.x = element_blank(),
          axis.line.y = element_line(color = "grey55"),
          legend.title = element_text(face = "bold", color = "grey80"),
          legend.text = element_text(color = "grey55"),
          panel.grid.major.x = element_line(color = "grey25", 
                                            linetype = "dotted", 
                                            size = .4),
          plot.margin = margin(20, 0, 20, 5))
pop_dance

Popular artists and what genre they belong to

I wanted to see the 120 most popular songs on spotify. I plotted a barchart to see which artists had the most popualar song, and also wanted to see which playlist genre most of their songs belonged to. From the analysis, Billie Eilish is the artist with most popular song and she her music is from several genres, the most common one being pop. For other artists, most songs are from the playlist genre pop.

spotify <- as.data.table(spotify)
pop_genre <- spotify[, .(playlist_genre, track_popularity, track_artist), ][order(-track_popularity)][1:120]


popular_artists <- ggplot(pop_genre, aes(x=track_artist, y=track_popularity))+
  geom_bar(aes(y=track_popularity, fill = playlist_genre), stat="identity") +
  labs(x="Artist", y="Popularity",
       title="Most popular artists") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))
popular_artists

Do different genres have difference valence?

The valence of the song is the sadness of music. It is a measure of positivity in the track and ranges from 0.0 to 1.0. High valence songs have more positive music attached to it. I was curious to see how difference genres vary in the valence they have in their songs. To do an analysis, I did a facet wrap of all genres side by side and plotted density map of valence.

valence_plot <- ggplot(spotify, aes(x = valence, y = playlist_genre, fill = playlist_genre)) + 
  geom_density_ridges(
    show.legend = FALSE,
    panel_scaling = FALSE,
    quantile_lines = TRUE,
    quantiles = c(.05, .95),
    alpha = .7
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~playlist_genre, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1)) +
  ggridges::theme_ridges() +
  labs(
    y = ""
  )

valence_plot

How are speechiness and popularity of the track related? And how has that changed over the years?

Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. I wanted to see how speechiness correlated with track popularity. And how that changed over the years. To do this, i changed the album release date column to have another year column. I drew a plot and transitioned it over the years. I also wanted to see the different genres for each track so I coloured it according to genre.

spotify2 <- spotify %>%
  separate(track_album_release_date, sep="-", into = c("year", "month", "day"))

class(spotify2$year)
## [1] "character"
spotify2 <- spotify2 %>% transform(year = as.numeric(year))


p <- ggplot(spotify2, 
  aes(x =speechiness , y=track_popularity, colour = playlist_genre)
  ) +
  geom_point(show.legend = TRUE, alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  scale_size(range = c(2, 12)) +
  scale_x_log10()
p

Circular bar plots of artists based on the popularity of their music

To see which sub_genre was the most popular i plotted circular bar plots with mean popularity of all tracks in that subgenre. The comparison shows us which genres have more popularity and we can draw a direct comparison in one graph.

spotify <- as.data.table(spotify)
subg <- spotify[, list(totalpop = mean(track_popularity, na.rm = TRUE)), 
         by = playlist_subgenre]

data <- data.frame(subg)
empty_bar <- 10
 
# Add lines to the initial dataset
to_add <- matrix(NA, empty_bar, ncol(data))
colnames(to_add) <- colnames(data)
data <- rbind(data, to_add)
data$id <- seq(1, nrow(data))
 
# Get the name and the y position of each label
label_data <- data
number_of_bar <- nrow(label_data)
angle <- 90 - 360 * (label_data$id-0.5) /number_of_bar    
label_data$hjust <- ifelse( angle < -90, 1, 0)
label_data$angle <- ifelse(angle < -90, angle+180, angle)
 
# Make the plot
p <- ggplot(data, aes(x=as.factor(playlist_subgenre), y=totalpop)) +    
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill=alpha("green", 0.3)) +
  ylim(-100,120) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    plot.margin = unit(rep(-1,4), "cm") 
  ) +
  coord_polar(start = 0) + 
  geom_text(data=label_data, aes(x=id, y=10, label=playlist_subgenre, hjust=hjust), color="black", fontface="bold",alpha=0.6, size=2.5, angle= label_data$angle, inherit.aes = FALSE ) 
 
p
